Here's how to cover all three requirements:

### 1. Detect the current system theme

```csharp
AppTheme current = Application.Current!.RequestedTheme;
// Returns AppTheme.Light, AppTheme.Dark, or AppTheme.Unspecified
```

### 2. Subscribe to real-time theme changes & log them

```csharp
// In your App constructor or OnStart:
Application.Current!.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {e.RequestedTheme}");
    // Update UI, swap ResourceDictionaries, etc.
};
```

### 3. Let the user force a theme

```csharp
// Force dark mode
Application.Current!.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Force light mode
Application.Current!.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Light;

// Follow the system again
Application.Current!.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

Persist the choice across launches:

```csharp
// Save
Preferences.Set("AppTheme", "Dark");

// Restore on startup
var saved = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "System");
Application.Current!.UserAppTheme = saved switch
{
    "Light" => AppTheme.Light,
    "Dark"  => AppTheme.Dark,
    _       => AppTheme.Unspecified
};
```

### ⚠️ Android pitfall

Your `MainActivity` **must** include `ConfigChanges.UiMode` or the `RequestedThemeChanged` event won't fire — Android will restart the activity instead:

```csharp
[Activity(ConfigurationChanges = ConfigChanges.ScreenSize
                               | ConfigChanges.Orientation
                               | ConfigChanges.UiMode   // ← required
                               | ConfigChanges.ScreenLayout
                               | ConfigChanges.SmallestScreenSize
                               | ConfigChanges.Density)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

Without it, toggling dark mode in device settings causes a full activity restart, losing navigation state.
